{"title_page": "Purple martin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| image = PurpleMartin_cajay.jpg\n| image_caption = Adult male\n| image2 = Progne subis -Chicago, USA -female-8.jpg\n| image2_caption = Adult female\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22712098/0 |title=''Progne subis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Progne\n| species = subis\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Progne subis map.svg\n| synonyms = ''Hirundo subis'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''purple martin''' (''Progne subis'') is the largest [[swallow]] in North America. Despite their name, purple martins are not truly purple. Their dark blackish-blue feathers have an iridescent sheen caused by the refraction of incident light <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gill|first=Frank B.|title=Ornithology|publisher=W. H. Freeman and Company|year=2007|isbn=0-7167-4983-1|location=New York, NY|pages=97-98}}</ref> giving them a bright blue to navy blue or deep purple appearance. In some light they may even appear green in color. \n\nTheir breeding range extends from central Alberta down through the eastern United States. Subspecies breed in Baja California, Arizona, and New Mexico. Purple martins are migratory [[passerine|passerines]]. Most make a brief stopover in the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula|Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] or [[Cuba]] during pre-breeding migration to North America and during post-breeding migration before reaching their overwintering site in South America.<ref name=\"Cornell\">{{cite web \n  | first = Charles R.\n  | last = Brown\n  | editor= Purple Martin (Progne subis)\n  | editor2= The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole\n  | publisher = Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n  | url= https://birdsna.org/Species-Account/bna/species/purmar/introduction\n  | title=Purple Martin - Introduction\n  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThey are known for their speed, agility, and their characteristic mix of rapid flapping and gliding flight pattern. When approaching their nesting site, they will dive from the sky at great speeds with their wings tucked.\n\n==Description and taxonomy==\nPurple martins are a kind of swallow, of the [[genus]] ''Progne''. With an average length of {{convert|20|cm|in|abbr=on}} and a wingspan up to {{convert|38|cm|in|abbr=on}}, they are also the largest amongst the 90 some species in the family [[Hirundinidae]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/animal/Hirundinidae|title=Hirundinidae {{!}} bird family|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> Purple martins are [[sexually dimorphic]]. Adult males are entirely black with glossy steel blue sheen, the only swallow in North America with such coloration. Adult females are dark on top with some steel blue sheen, and lighter underparts. Adults have a slightly forked tail. Both male and female purple martins exhibit [[delayed plumage maturation]], meaning it takes them two years before they acquire full adult plumage. Subadult females look similar to adult females minus the steel blue sheen and browner on the back. Subadult males look very much like females, but solid black feathers emerge on their chest in a blotchy, random pattern as they molt to their adult plumage.<ref name = \"Cornell\">{{cite web \n  | first = Charles R.\n  | last = Brown\n  | editor= Purple Martin (Progne subis)\n  | editor2= The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole\n  | publisher = Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n  | url= https://birdsna.org/Species-Account/bna/species/purmar/introduction\n  | title=Purple Martin - Introduction\n  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n</ref>  \n\nThis species was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] in his ''Systema naturae'' in [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]] as ''Hirundo subis''.<ref name=Linnaeus>Linnaeus (1758</ref> The current genus name refers to [[Procne]] (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03ba\u03bd\u03b7''), a [[Greek mythology|mythological]] girl who was turned into a swallow to save her from her husband. She had killed their son to avenge the rape of her sister. The specific ''subis'' is [[Latin]] and refers to a type of bird that breaks eagles\u2019 eggs; it may have been applied to this species because of its aggression towards birds of prey when it is nesting.<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n317 317], 371}}</ref>\n\nThe species of this genus are very closely related, and some view the purple martin, gray-breasted martin, snowy-bellied martin, and southern martin, as a [[superspecies]].<ref name = \"Turner\">\n{{Cite book\n  | last1 = Turner\n  | first1 = Angela K.\n  | last2 = Rose\n  | first2 = Chris\n  | title = Swallows & Martins\n  | publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin]]\n  | year = 1989\n  | location = Boston\n  | pages = [https://archive.org/details/swallowsmartinsi00turn/page/7 7, 123\u2013126]\n  | isbn = 0-395-51174-7\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/swallowsmartinsi00turn/page/7\n  }}</ref>\n\n===Subspecies===\n* ''P. s. subis'', is the nominate form, with the typical features of the species, breeds in eastern and mid-western North America.\n* ''P. s. hesperia'' of the [[Mexico]] and the southwestern [[United States]], is distinguished primarily by its nesting habits.\n* ''P. s. arboricola'' of western mountains is large with females paler on underparts.\n\n===Distribution and habitat===\n[[File:Progne subis -fledglings -Tulsa -Oklahoma-8.jpg|left|thumb|Fledglings in Oklahoma, United States]]\nPurple martins' breeding range is throughout temperate North America.<ref>Attenborough, D. ''The Life of Birds.'' 1998. BBC p 297. {{ISBN|0563-38792-0}}</ref> Their breeding [[habitat]] is open areas across eastern North America, and also some locations on the west coast from [[British Columbia]] to [[Mexico]].<ref>See AOU (2000) for details.</ref> Martins make their [[Bird nest|nest]]s in cavities, either natural or artificial. In many places, humans put up real or artificial hollow gourds, or houses for martins, especially in the east, where purple martins are almost entirely dependent on such structures. As a result, this subspecies typically breeds in [[Bird colony|colonies]] located in proximity to people, even within cities and towns. This makes their distribution patchy, as they are usually absent from areas where no nest sites are provided. Western birds often make use of natural cavities such as old woodpecker holes in trees or [[saguaro]] cacti.<ref name = \"Cornell\"/><ref name = \"Turner\"/>\n\nThe purple martin [[bird migration|migrates]] to the [[Amazon River|Amazon]] basin in winter. Its winter range extends into [[Ecuador]]<ref>[[Guayas Province|Guayas]] and [[Orellana Province]]s: Cisneros-Heredia (2006).</ref> but does not seem to ascend far up the [[Andes|Andean]] foothills.\n\nThe first record of this species in [[Europe]] was a single bird on [[Isle of Lewis|Lewis]], [[Scotland]], on 5\u20136 September 2004, and the second was on the [[Azores]] on 6 September 2004.\n\n==Conservation status==\nPurple martins suffered a severe population crash in the 20th century widely linked to the release and spread of [[European starling]]s in North America. European starlings and [[house sparrow]]s compete with martins for nest cavities. Where purple martins once gathered by the thousands, by the 1980s they had all but disappeared.\n<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Hunn\n  |first = Eugene S.\n  |title = Birding in Seattle and King County\n  |publisher = [[Seattle Audubon Society]]\n  |year = 1982\n  |isbn = 0914516051\n  |pages = 107\u2013108\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThere is a misconception among many people of purple martin temperament. Many people believe purple martins will defend their nesting sites against competitor species such as the [[house sparrow]] and [[European starling]]. However, both species are more aggressive and in most cases will instinctively fight to the death in order to obtain a nesting site. The house sparrow and European starling are known to kill adult martins, take over the nest and remove eggs or remaining young.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"155px\">\nFile:Progne subis -Tulsa, Oklahoma, USA -nestboxes-8.ogv|Adults around gourds and [[nest box]]es in a garden in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], United States\nFile:Griggsville, Illinois.jpg|Nest boxes in Griggsville, Illinois\n</gallery>Though listed as \u2018Least Concern\u2019 with the IUCN<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Purple Martin|last=International)|first=BirdLife International (BirdLife|date=2016-10-01|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>, purple martins are experiencing a unique threat to their long-term survival. Nearly all eastern species exclusively nest in artificial gourds and \u2018condo\u2019 units provided by human \u2018landlords\u2019. A practice that has been experiencing a steady decline in the number of \u2018landlords\u2019 offering nesting sites. One study found that nearly 90% of landlords were 50 years of age or older, and that younger generations were not exhibiting the same enthusiasm nor possess the resources to provided martin housing for the species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Jervis|first=L.|date=2019|title=Resisting Extinction: Purple Martins, Death, and the Future|url=|journal=Conservation and Society|volume=17|pages=227-235|via=ProQuest}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with humans===\nPurple martins (nominate form ''P. s. subis'') are considered [[Synanthrope|synanthropic]], meaning they have developed an association with humans overtime and benefit from living in close proximity to them <ref name=\":0\" />. Through years of generational imprinting and nesting the eastern species has made a complete transition from nesting in the wild to relying on human-provided nesting sites. Initially difficult to get a colony started, once established, the colony will persist as long as nesting sites are available. Martins have a very strong \"site tenacity\" and if are successful in raising a brood, will often return to the same site to nest year after year <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chuckspurplemartinpage.com|title=The Purple Martin Progne subis subis|last=Abare|first=Chuck|date=|website=Chuck's Purple Martin Page|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nThe human-avian relationship was in place even before the population crash in the 20th century; The Cherokee Indians were known to have hollowed out the gourds in the pre-colonial era. They erected them so that the adult birds would build nests and then feed thousands of insects to their young each day that would otherwise be eating their crops. In 1808, [[Chickasaw|Chickasaws]] and [[Choctaw|Choctaws]] were observed hanging gourds for martins on stripped saplings near their cabins, as were African Americans on long canes on the banks of the Mississippi<ref name=\":0\" />.   \n\nContinual maintenance and protection is required, as European starlings and house sparrows compete with martins as cavity-nesters, and will fight with martins over nest sites. Thus, unmonitored purple martin houses are often overtaken by more aggressive, non-native species.<ref name=\"Cornell\" /> Purple martin proponents are motivated by the concern that the purple martin would likely vanish from eastern North America were it not for this assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://purplemartin.org/main/history.html|title=Purple Martin Conservation Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120730212222/http://purplemartin.org/main/history.html|archivedate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior==\n\n===Migration===\nWintering in Brazil, Bolivia and parts of Peru <ref name=\"Cornell\" />, purple martins migrate to North America in the spring to breed. Spring migration is somewhat staggered, with arrivals in southern areas such as [[Florida]] and [[Texas]] in January, but showing up in the northern United States in April and in [[Canada]] as late as May. \n\nArrival date to the breeding grounds tends to correlate directly with age. It is assumed that the older birds arrive on the breeding grounds first to obtain the better nesting sites. Older males typically migrate first and leave the overwintering sites in late December or early January, followed by older females. Younger birds (first yearlings) typically arrive to the breeding grounds up to two months later <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Morton|first=E. S.|date=1990|title=The Biological Significance of Age-Specific Return Schedules in Breeding Purple Martins|url=https://doi.org/10.2307/1368740|journal=The Condor|volume=92|pages=1040-1050|via=JSTOR}}</ref>.  \n\nFall migration is also staggered, as birds head south when the breeding season is over. Some birds leave as early as July and others stay as late as October. Martins generally migrate over land, through Mexico and [[Central America]]. When not breeding, martins form large flocks and roost together in great numbers. This behavior begins just prior to the southern migration and continues on the wintering grounds.<ref name=\"Cornell\" />\n\nThese flocks can be so large that when they take-off from these roosts to forage the activity is detected on Doppler radar as rings. Referred to as [[roost rings]], they start small then get larger until the birds have spread out and the ring disappears <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=K.R.|date=1998|title=Large-Scale Mapping of Purple Martin Pre-Migratory Roosts Using WSR-88D Weather Surveillance Radar (Mapas a Larga Escala De Los Dormideros Pre-Migratorios De Progne Subis Utilizando Radares WSR-88D Para El Monitoreo Del Clima|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4514321?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume=69|pages=316-325|via=JSTOR}}</ref>.\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Progne subis -Tulsa, Oklahoma, USA -eggs and chicks in nestbox-8.jpg|right|thumb|Eggs and small chicks in a nest box in [[Oklahoma]], United States]]\nMales arrive in breeding sites before females, and establish their [[Territory (animal)|territory]]. A territory can consist of several potential nest sites. After forming a pair, both the male and female inspect available nest sites. This process is complicated by the fact that artificial nest sites could be houses with many rooms, clustered gourds, or single gourds. The nest is made inside the cavity of such artificial structures and retains a somewhat flat appearance. The nest is a structure of primarily three levels: the first level acts as a foundation and is usually made up of twigs, mud, small pebbles and in at least a few reported cases, small river mollusk shells were used; the second level of the nest is made up of grasses, finer smaller twigs; the third level of construction composing the nest, is a small compression usually lined with fresh green leaves where the eggs are laid.\n\nPurple martins are generally known to raise only a single brood. The average clutch size is four to six eggs per nest. Females lay one egg a day and incubation begins when the penultimate (second to last) egg is laid. Incubation lasts 15-16 days and the female is the main incubator, with some help from the male. Hatching occurs over the course of two to three days. Fledging, when the young leave the nest, occurs between 26-32 days after hatch day. [[Fledge|Fledglings]] will continue to receive care from both parents for up to a month after fledging. \n\n===Diet===\nPurple martins are [[insectivore]]s, primarily feed by [[Hawking (birds)|hawking]], a strategy of catching insects in the air during flight. The birds are agile hunters and eat a variety of winged insects. Rarely, they will come to the ground to eat insects. They usually fly relatively high, so, contrary to popular opinion, [[mosquito]]es do not form a large part of their diet.<ref name = \"Cornell\"/> Recent research, however, does indicate that the Purple Martin feeds on invasive fire ants ([[Solenopsis invicta]]) and that they may make up a significant portion of their diet.<ref>Helms IV, Jackson A., Bridge, Eli S., Godfrey, Aaron P, and Ames, Tayna. (2015): The Purple Martin Update. \"Fire Ant Exterminators\". 24-27.</ref>\n\n<br />\n===Vocalization===\n{{listen|filename=Progne-subis-001.ogg|title=Purple martin|description=}}\n{{listen|filename=Purple_Martins_(Progne_subis).ogg|title=Purple martin}}\n\nPurple martins are fairly noisy, chirping and making sounds that have been described as chortles, rattles, and croaks.<ref name = \"Turner\"/> The various calls are said to be \"throaty and rich\" and can be rendered as ''tchew-wew'', ''pew pew'', ''choo'', ''cher'', ''zweet'' and ''zwrack''. The males have a gurgling and guttural courtship song, a dawn song, and even a subsong used at the end of the breeding season.<ref name = \"Turner\"/><ref>Peterson (1980): p.202</ref> Tapes of purple martin song are sold to attract martins to newly established birdhouses.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n<!-- WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf) -->\n* [[American Ornithologists' Union]] (AOU) (2000). Forty-second supplement to the American Ornithologists' Union Check-list of North American Birds. ''[[Auk (journal)|Auk]]'' '''117'''(3): 847\u2013858. <small>[[Digital Object Identifier|DOI]]: 10.1642/0004-8038(2000)117[0847:FSSTTA]2.0.CO;2</small>\n* Cisneros-Heredia, Diego F. (2006). \"[http://www.sao.org.co/publicaciones/boletinsao/02CisnerosEcuador.pdf Informaci\u00f3n sobre la distribuci\u00f3n de algunas especies de aves de Ecuador]\". [\"Information on the distribution of some species of birds of Ecuador\"]. ''Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Antioque\u00f1a de Ornitolog\u00eda'' '''16'''(1): 7-16. [Spanish with English abstract]\n*{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carolus | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. | language = Latin |publisher=Holmiae. (Laurentii Salvii). | year=1758| pages=192}}\n* Peterson, Roger Tory (1980). ''A Completely New Guide to All the Birds of Eastern and Central North America'' (4th ed.). Houghton Mifflin, Boston. {{ISBN|99975-1-436-X}}.<!--Technically valid; shows up correctly on Amazon; but group name of \"Tajikistan\" means there might be something off here.-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Progne subis|Purple martin}}\n{{Wikispecies|Progne subis}}\n* [http://www.purplemartin.org/ Purple Martin Conservation Association]\n* [http://www.naturesociety.org/ The Nature Society] purple martin monthly publication and information\n* [http://www.purplemartins.com/ The Purple Martin Society, NA]\n* [http://www.bird-stamps.org/cspecies/12300400.htm Stamps] (for [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]) at bird-stamps.org\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|purple-martin-progne-subis|Purple Martin}}\n* [http://birds.audubon.org/species/purmar How to Help Purple Martins] - National Audubon Society\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131202234225/http://www.hww.ca/en/species/birds/purple-martin.html Purple Martin] at Hinterland's Who's Who (Environment Canada & The Canadian Wildlife Federation)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121008151116/http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/wwwsounds/birds/hardy46sh.wav Purple Martin Bird Sound] at Florida Museum of Natural History\n* {{VIREO|Purple+Martin|Purple Martin}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BiPJSvpSxV0 10-Minute Timelapse from June-July 2017 observing nest development from eggs to fledglings]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TvU7c_9xuXE 13-Minute Season Re-cap from May-July 2018 observing one nest of three new Purple Martins]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/PurpleMartinPMCA/live Purple Martin NestCam 2019]  A live webcam follows activity during June-July in a nest at the Purple Martin Conservation Association HQ in Erie, PA, USA\n\n{{Hirundinidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1062485}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, purple}}\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758]]\n[[Category:Birds of North America]]\n[[Category:Birds of South America]]\n[[Category:Birds of the United States]]\n[[Category:Progne]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| image = PurpleMartin_cajay.jpg\n| image_caption = Adult male\n| image2 = Progne subis -Chicago, USA -female-8.jpg\n| image2_caption = Adult female\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22712098/0 |title=''Progne subis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Progne\n| species = subis\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Progne subis map.svg\n| synonyms = ''Hirundo subis'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''purple martin''' (''Progne subis'') is the largest [[swallow]] in North America. Despite their name, purple martins are not truly purple. Their dark blackish-blue feathers have an iridescent sheen caused by the refraction of incident light <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gill|first=Frank B.|title=Ornithology|publisher=W. H. Freeman and Company|year=2007|isbn=0-7167-4983-1|location=New York, NY|pages=97-98}}</ref> giving them a bright blue to navy blue or deep purple appearance. In some light they may even appear green in color. \n\nTheir breeding range extends from central Alberta down through the eastern United States. Subspecies breed in Baja California, Arizona, and New Mexico. Purple martins are migratory [[passerine|passerines]]. Most make a brief stopover in the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula|Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] or [[Cuba]] during pre-breeding migration to North America and during post-breeding migration before reaching their overwintering site in South America.<ref name=\"Cornell\">{{cite web \n  | first = Charles R.\n  | last = Brown\n  | editor= Purple Martin (Progne subis)\n  | editor2= The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole\n  | publisher = Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n  | url= https://birdsna.org/Species-Account/bna/species/purmar/introduction\n  | title=Purple Martin - Introduction\n  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThey are known for their speed, agility, and their characteristic mix of rapid flapping and gliding flight pattern. When approaching their nesting site, they will dive from the sky at great speeds with their wings tucked.\n\n==Description and taxonomy==\nPurple martins are a kind of swallow, of the [[genus]] ''Progne''. With an average length of {{convert|20|cm|in|abbr=on}} and a wingspan up to {{convert|38|cm|in|abbr=on}}, they are also the largest amongst the 90 some species in the family [[Hirundinidae]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/animal/Hirundinidae|title=Hirundinidae {{!}} bird family|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> Purple martins are [[sexually dimorphic]]. Adult males are entirely black with glossy steel blue sheen, the only swallow in North America with such coloration. Adult females are dark on top with some steel blue sheen, and lighter underparts. Adults have a slightly forked tail. Both male and female purple martins exhibit [[delayed plumage maturation]], meaning it takes them two years before they acquire full adult plumage. Subadult females look similar to adult females minus the steel blue sheen and browner on the back. Subadult males look very much like females, but solid black feathers emerge on their chest in a blotchy, random pattern as they molt to their adult plumage.<ref name = \"Cornell\">{{cite web \n  | first = Charles R.\n  | last = Brown\n  | editor= Purple Martin (Progne subis)\n  | editor2= The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole\n  | publisher = Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n  | url= https://birdsna.org/Species-Account/bna/species/purmar/introduction\n  | title=Purple Martin - Introduction\n  | accessdate=1 November 2009}}\n</ref>  \n\nThis species was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] in his ''Systema naturae'' in [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]] as ''Hirundo subis''.<ref name=Linnaeus>Linnaeus (1758</ref> The current genus name refers to [[Procne]] (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03ba\u03bd\u03b7''), a [[Greek mythology|mythological]] girl who was turned into a swallow to save her from her husband. She had killed their son to avenge the rape of her sister. The specific ''subis'' is [[Latin]] and refers to a type of bird that breaks eagles\u2019 eggs; it may have been applied to this species because of its aggression towards birds of prey when it is nesting.<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n317 317], 371}}</ref>\n\nThe species of this genus are very closely related, and some view the purple martin, gray-breasted martin, snowy-bellied martin, and southern martin, as a [[superspecies]].<ref name = \"Turner\">\n{{Cite book\n  | last1 = Turner\n  | first1 = Angela K.\n  | last2 = Rose\n  | first2 = Chris\n  | title = Swallows & Martins\n  | publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin]]\n  | year = 1989\n  | location = Boston\n  | pages = [https://archive.org/details/swallowsmartinsi00turn/page/7 7, 123\u2013126]\n  | isbn = 0-395-51174-7\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/swallowsmartinsi00turn/page/7\n  }}</ref>\n\n===Subspecies===\n* ''P. s. subis'', is the nominate form, with the typical features of the species, breeds in eastern and mid-western North America.\n* ''P. s. hesperia'' of the [[Mexico]] and the southwestern [[United States]], is distinguished primarily by its nesting habits.\n* ''P. s. arboricola'' of western mountains is large with females paler on underparts.\n\n===Distribution and habitat===\n[[File:Progne subis -fledglings -Tulsa -Oklahoma-8.jpg|left|thumb|Fledglings in Oklahoma, United States]]\nPurple martins' breeding range is throughout temperate North America.<ref>Attenborough, D. ''The Life of Birds.'' 1998. BBC p 297. {{ISBN|0563-38792-0}}</ref> Their breeding [[habitat]] is open areas across eastern North America, and also some locations on the west coast from [[British Columbia]] to [[Mexico]].<ref>See AOU (2000) for details.</ref> Martins make their [[Bird nest|nest]]s in cavities, either natural or artificial. In many places, humans put up real or artificial hollow gourds, or houses for martins, especially in the east, where purple martins are almost entirely dependent on such structures. As a result, this subspecies typically breeds in [[Bird colony|colonies]] located in proximity to people, even within cities and towns. This makes their distribution patchy, as they are usually absent from areas where no nest sites are provided. Western birds often make use of natural cavities such as old woodpecker holes in trees or [[saguaro]] cacti.<ref name = \"Cornell\"/><ref name = \"Turner\"/>\n\nThe purple martin [[bird migration|migrates]] to the [[Amazon River|Amazon]] basin in winter. Its winter range extends into [[Ecuador]]<ref>[[Guayas Province|Guayas]] and [[Orellana Province]]s: Cisneros-Heredia (2006).</ref> but does not seem to ascend far up the [[Andes|Andean]] foothills.\n\nThe first record of this species in [[Europe]] was a single bird on [[Isle of Lewis|Lewis]], [[Scotland]], on 5\u20136 September 2004, and the second was on the [[Azores]] on 6 September 2004.\n\n==Conservation status==\nPurple martins suffered a severe population crash in the 20th century widely linked to the release and spread of [[European starling]]s in North America. European starlings and [[house sparrow]]s compete with martins for nest cavities. Where purple martins once gathered by the thousands, by the 1980s they had all but disappeared.\n<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Hunn\n  |first = Eugene S.\n  |title = Birding in Seattle and King County\n  |publisher = [[Seattle Audubon Society]]\n  |year = 1982\n  |isbn = 0914516051\n  |pages = 107\u2013108\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThere is a misconception among many people of purple martin temperament. Many people believe purple martins will defend their nesting sites against competitor species such as the [[house sparrow]] and [[European starling]]. However, both species are more aggressive and in most cases will instinctively fight to the death in order to obtain a nesting site. The house sparrow and European starling are known to kill adult martins, take over the nest and remove eggs or remaining young.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"155px\">\nFile:Progne subis -Tulsa, Oklahoma, USA -nestboxes-8.ogv|Adults around gourds and [[nest box]]es in a garden in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], United States\nFile:Griggsville, Illinois.jpg|Nest boxes in Griggsville, Illinois\n</gallery>Though listed as \u2018Least Concern\u2019 with the IUCN<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Purple Martin|last=International)|first=BirdLife International (BirdLife|date=2016-10-01|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>, purple martins are experiencing a unique threat to their long-term survival. Nearly all eastern species exclusively nest in artificial gourds and \u2018condo\u2019 units provided by human \u2018landlords\u2019. A practice that has been experiencing a steady decline in the number of \u2018landlords\u2019 offering nesting sites. One study found that nearly 90% of landlords were 50 years of age or older, and that younger generations were not exhibiting the same enthusiasm nor possess the resources to provided martin housing for the species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Jervis|first=L.|date=2019|title=Resisting Extinction: Purple Martins, Death, and the Future|url=|journal=Conservation and Society|volume=17|pages=227-235|via=ProQuest}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with humans===\nPurple martins (nominate form ''P. s. subis'') are considered [[Synanthrope|synanthropic]], meaning they have developed an association with humans overtime and benefit from living in close proximity to them <ref name=\":0\" />. Through years of generational imprinting and nesting the eastern species has made a complete transition from nesting in the wild to relying on human-provided nesting sites. Initially difficult to get a colony started, once established, the colony will persist as long as nesting sites are available. Martins have a very strong \"site tenacity\" and if are successful in raising a brood, will often return to the same site to nest year after year <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chuckspurplemartinpage.com|title=The Purple Martin Progne subis subis|last=Abare|first=Chuck|date=|website=Chuck's Purple Martin Page|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nThe human-avian relationship was in place even before the population crash in the 20th century; The Cherokee Indians were known to have hollowed out the gourds in the pre-colonial era. They erected them so that the adult birds would build nests and then feed thousands of insects to their young each day that would otherwise be eating their crops. In 1808, [[Chickasaw|Chickasaws]] and [[Choctaw|Choctaws]] were observed hanging gourds for martins on stripped saplings near their cabins, as were African Americans on long canes on the banks of the Mississippi<ref name=\":0\" />.   \n\nContinual maintenance and protection is required, as European starlings and house sparrows compete with martins as cavity-nesters, and will fight with martins over nest sites. Thus, unmonitored purple martin houses are often overtaken by more aggressive, non-native species.<ref name=\"Cornell\" /> Purple martin proponents are motivated by the concern that the purple martin would likely vanish from eastern North America were it not for this assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://purplemartin.org/main/history.html|title=Purple Martin Conservation Association|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120730212222/http://purplemartin.org/main/history.html|archivedate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior==\n\n===Migration===\nWintering in Brazil, Bolivia and parts of Peru <ref name=\"Cornell\" />, purple martins migrate to North America in the spring to breed. Spring migration is somewhat staggered, with arrivals in southern areas such as [[Florida]] and [[Texas]] in January, but showing up in the northern United States in April and in [[Canada]] as late as May. \n\nArrival date to the breeding grounds tends to correlate directly with age. It is assumed that the older birds arrive on the breeding grounds first to obtain the better nesting sites. Older males typically migrate first and leave the overwintering sits in late December or early January, followed by older females. Younger birds (first yearlings) typically arrive to the breeding grounds up to two months later <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Morton|first=E. S.|date=1990|title=The Biological Significance of Age-Specific Return Schedules in Breeding Purple Martins|url=https://doi.org/10.2307/1368740|journal=The Condor|volume=92|pages=1040-1050|via=JSTOR}}</ref>.  \n\nFall migration is also staggered, as birds head south when the breeding season is over. Some birds leave as early as July and others stay as late as October. Martins generally migrate over land, through Mexico and [[Central America]]. When not breeding, martins form large flocks and roost together in great numbers. This behavior begins just prior to the southern migration and continues on the wintering grounds.<ref name=\"Cornell\" />\n\nThese flocks can be so large that when they take-off from these roosts to forage the activity is detected on Doppler radar as rings. Referred to as [[roost rings]], they start small then get larger until the birds have spread out and the ring disappears <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=K.R.|date=1998|title=Large-Scale Mapping of Purple Martin Pre-Migratory Roosts Using WSR-88D Weather Surveillance Radar (Mapas a Larga Escala De Los Dormideros Pre-Migratorios De Progne Subis Utilizando Radares WSR-88D Para El Monitoreo Del Clima|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4514321?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume=69|pages=316-325|via=JSTOR}}</ref>.\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Progne subis -Tulsa, Oklahoma, USA -eggs and chicks in nestbox-8.jpg|right|thumb|Eggs and small chicks in a nest box in [[Oklahoma]], United States]]\nMales arrive in breeding sites before females, and establish their [[Territory (animal)|territory]]. A territory can consist of several potential nest sites. After forming a pair, both the male and female inspect available nest sites. This process is complicated by the fact that artificial nest sites could be houses with many rooms, clustered gourds, or single gourds. The nest is made inside the cavity of such artificial structures and retains a somewhat flat appearance. The nest is a structure of primarily three levels: the first level acts as a foundation and is usually made up of twigs, mud, small pebbles and in at least a few reported cases, small river mollusk shells were used; the second level of the nest is made up of grasses, finer smaller twigs; the third level of construction composing the nest, is a small compression usually lined with fresh green leaves where the eggs are laid.\n\nPurple martins are generally known to raise only a single brood. The average clutch size is four to six eggs per nest. Females lay one egg a day and incubation begins when the penultimate (second to last) egg is laid. Incubation lasts 15-16 days and the female is the main incubator, with some help from the male. Hatching occurs over the course of two to three days. Fledging, when the young leave the nest, occurs between 26-32 days after hatch day. [[Fledge|Fledglings]] will continue to receive care from both parents for up to a month after fledging. \n\n===Diet===\nPurple martins are [[insectivore]]s, primarily feed by [[Hawking (birds)|hawking]], a strategy of catching insects in the air during flight. The birds are agile hunters and eat a variety of winged insects. Rarely, they will come to the ground to eat insects. They usually fly relatively high, so, contrary to popular opinion, [[mosquito]]es do not form a large part of their diet.<ref name = \"Cornell\"/> Recent research, however, does indicate that the Purple Martin feeds on invasive fire ants ([[Solenopsis invicta]]) and that they may make up a significant portion of their diet.<ref>Helms IV, Jackson A., Bridge, Eli S., Godfrey, Aaron P, and Ames, Tayna. (2015): The Purple Martin Update. \"Fire Ant Exterminators\". 24-27.</ref>\n\n<br />\n===Vocalization===\n{{listen|filename=Progne-subis-001.ogg|title=Purple martin|description=}}\n{{listen|filename=Purple_Martins_(Progne_subis).ogg|title=Purple martin}}\n\nPurple martins are fairly noisy, chirping and making sounds that have been described as chortles, rattles, and croaks.<ref name = \"Turner\"/> The various calls are said to be \"throaty and rich\" and can be rendered as ''tchew-wew'', ''pew pew'', ''choo'', ''cher'', ''zweet'' and ''zwrack''. The males have a gurgling and guttural courtship song, a dawn song, and even a subsong used at the end of the breeding season.<ref name = \"Turner\"/><ref>Peterson (1980): p.202</ref> Tapes of purple martin song are sold to attract martins to newly established birdhouses.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n<!-- WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf) -->\n* [[American Ornithologists' Union]] (AOU) (2000). Forty-second supplement to the American Ornithologists' Union Check-list of North American Birds. ''[[Auk (journal)|Auk]]'' '''117'''(3): 847\u2013858. <small>[[Digital Object Identifier|DOI]]: 10.1642/0004-8038(2000)117[0847:FSSTTA]2.0.CO;2</small>\n* Cisneros-Heredia, Diego F. (2006). \"[http://www.sao.org.co/publicaciones/boletinsao/02CisnerosEcuador.pdf Informaci\u00f3n sobre la distribuci\u00f3n de algunas especies de aves de Ecuador]\". [\"Information on the distribution of some species of birds of Ecuador\"]. ''Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Antioque\u00f1a de Ornitolog\u00eda'' '''16'''(1): 7-16. [Spanish with English abstract]\n*{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carolus | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. | language = Latin |publisher=Holmiae. (Laurentii Salvii). | year=1758| pages=192}}\n* Peterson, Roger Tory (1980). ''A Completely New Guide to All the Birds of Eastern and Central North America'' (4th ed.). Houghton Mifflin, Boston. {{ISBN|99975-1-436-X}}.<!--Technically valid; shows up correctly on Amazon; but group name of \"Tajikistan\" means there might be something off here.-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Progne subis|Purple martin}}\n{{Wikispecies|Progne subis}}\n* [http://www.purplemartin.org/ Pu